(48, 'edit', 'How do I finish/correct a PURSUIT race result', '&lt;div &gt; Finishing a pursuit race is a little different from ordinary races - because a single fixed finish line does not produce a fair finish.  There are two types of finish you can use.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt; &lt;div style=&quot;margin-left: 30px&quot;&gt; &lt;b&gt;Moving Finish:&lt;/b&gt; This is the preferred approach form club pursuit races.  You can use this approach if only one RIB can be allocated to finishing.  In this case the finishing RIB tracks the leading boat - when the end of the race is signalled from the OOD box.  The RIB motors back from the finishing boat around the course in the reverse direction as quickly as possible, finishing boats as they pass them.  This is relatively easy to do on downwind legs, but harder to do on windward legs.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;Multiple Finish Lines:&lt;/b&gt;  If you have a large number of competitors a better approach is to set up several fixed finishing lines.  A RIB (No. 1) tracks the leading boat.  A few minutes before the scheduled end of the race it creates a finish line at what will be the NEXT buoy for the leading boat.  At the same time RIBs No. 2 and No. 3 set up finish lines at the two preceeding buoys on the course.  This is coordinated by the OOD box or RIB No. 1 (decide this well before the end of the race!).  Each RIB finishes the finishing order of boats that cross the finish line at their buoy. [Note: you can use the club finish line as one of the finish lines - but record the finishing order on paper]. It makes sense to have one person at each finishing line recording finishing positions on paper and if possible the other person on some sort of speech recording device.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Now follow these steps:&lt;/div&gt;', '&lt;div&gt; &lt;ol&gt; &lt;li&gt;When the results from each finish line get ashore you need to enter the finishing sequence - note that this may not be the same as the overall position as some