(49, 'results', 'How do I get OOD points', 'Go back to the Enter page, click the relevant fleet tab, and enter yourself (and the safety boat teams if relevant).  Now go to the Edit page and again click the relevant fleet and set the code for the boats you have just entered to OOD.  This will ensure that they get average points if this race is part of a series.\r\n', 'OOD points should be applied to any boats sailed by the OOD, assistant OOD, Safety Boay drivers and crews, and members on galley or bar duty.  It is not your responsibility as OOD to identify everyone who should get average points - they need to ask.', '', '', '', '', 'mark elkington', 2),
(50, 'timer', 'How do I use easyTimer?', 'WARNING - this is still a prototype function&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\r\n&lt;b&gt;easyTimer&lt;/b&gt; is an alternative approach to recording lap times which has some advantages if you have a big fleet as it avoids having to scroll the screen - it may not be available in your system.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\r\nClick the easyTimer button and you will see a screen where the boats are organised in columns by sail number.  Hover the mouse over a sail number and you''ll see the boat details.  Click on the sail number and it will record a lap/finish as for the normal Timer page.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\r\nWarnings will be displayed as for the Timer page and you can UNDO your last timing.  It doesn''t allow you to set a race code (OCS, DNF etc.) and you''ll need to switch back to the Timer page to do that.  You can flick backwards and forwards between the Timer, quickTimer and easyTimer at will - use the one that suits you best. ', 'For experienced OODs - you can use easyTimer to adjust the sequence of timings during a race.  Click on the Sequence button, select the boat you want to move and then select the number of seconds you want to add or subtract from their time - click Change to apply the change.', '', '', '', '', 'mark elkington', 5);
